Ewing Is Stepping Up In a Timely Fashion BASKETBALL NEW YORK KNICKERBOCKERS EWING, PATRICK DIAMOS, JASON Top/News Top/News/Sports Top/News/Sports/Pro Basketball Basketball Ewing Is Stepping Up In a Timely Fashion By JASON DIAMOS, DIAMOS, JASON MINNEAPOLIS, Dec. 31

After undergoing off-season arthroscopic surgery on his right knee, it has taken Patrick Ewing nearly a third of the regular season to once again feel comfortable on the court.

As far as the Knicks are concerned, the 7-footer's resurgence could not have come at a better time.

After undergoing off-season arthroscopic surgery on his right knee, it has taken Patrick Ewing nearly a third of the regular season to once again feel comfortable on the court.

As far as the Knicks are concerned, the 7-footer's resurgence could not have come at a better time.

With their frontcourt depleted by injuries to the All-Star power forward Charles Oakley (toe surgery) and the backup center Herb Williams (finger surgery) that will keep both out for at least the next month, the Knicks have increasingly turned to Ewing for the leadership that has made him an All-Star eight times in his nine seasons in the league. And the big man has responded.

On Friday night at Target Center, Ewing, playing all but four minutes, tied his season-high with 30 points, grabbed 12 rebounds and led a comeback from 16 points down early on. He led the Knicks (15-12) to their third straight victory after five consecutive losses, a hard-fought 90-81 decision over the Minnesota Timberwolves (6-20).

For Ewing, it was the second time in a row -- and third in four games -- that he has scored 30 points after he had not reached the 30-point plateau once in the Knicks' first 23 games. Ewing scored 30 or more 19 times last season.

"Coach Riley is calling a lot of things for Patrick right now," said point guard Derek Harper. "And for a good reason. Patrick deserves the ball. When he's going well, it allows us to play off of him and then we get a lot of comfortable looks ourselves."

Ewing, 32, missed all the exhibition games and practiced sparingly during the preseason because of the off-season surgical procedure. After Friday's game, he admitted that he is finally coming around.

"My knee definitely feels a lot better," Ewing said. "It's not hurting anymore. I'm feeling good. My shot is falling."

Ewing was 12 for 19 from the field Friday night and is 26 for 38 in his last two games. He, his coach and his teammates attribute Ewing's recent play to the fact that the Knicks are involving him in the offense more than they did earlier in the season.

"Because I missed the preseason, the guys were used to going to other people," Ewing said. "Now, they're accustomed to me being there again and they are looking for me."

Pat Riley said: "I don't know if Patrick was really ready early on. We were sort of in this flow without him early. Charles Smith was playing great, John Starks had a great preseason and Derek Harper had one of his best starts. Now, I think Patrick's getting everything back. We're going to run a lot of the offense through him. He's picking out guys, finding our jump shooters, doing a good job. He's got to hold the fort."

Ewing was at his best Friday during a 16-4 run midway through the third quarter, scoring 9 points as New York turned a 3-point deficit into a 65-56 lead. The Knicks held the Timberwolves without a field goal during the spurt, covering a span of 5 minutes 49 seconds.

And with Ewing dominating once again, opponents have resorted to collapsing on him, opening things up for his teammates. Harper had 17 points and 7 assists, Smith had 16 points in 41 minutes and Starks added 14 points (on 4 for 14 shooting), 7 rebounds and 7 assists.

"When Patrick gets rolling, it makes our jobs a lot easier," Starks said. "We're moving the ball around. And we can lick our chops while we line up and wait for our shots." REBOUNDS

The Knicks were off Saturday and Sunday. Their next game is Wednesday against Atlanta at Madison Square Garden. . . . Friday's game was PAT RILEY's 1,000th as a head coach. His career record is 716-284. . . . ISAIAH RIDER, Minnesota's leading scorer, spent part of New Year's Eve performing janitorial and secretarial chores at a detoxification center to fulfill a court sentence. Rider was sentenced Sept. 7 to perform 35 hours of community service for fifth-degree assault and disorderly conduct. Before today, he had worked off only seven hours and will face jail time if he doesn't fulfill the sentence by the end of the first week of January. . . . Riley was upset with the play of GREG ANTHONY, who missed all four of his shots (3 of which were 3-point attempts) in six first-half minutes. BASKETBALL
